# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: t-slot-nut
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:t-slot-nut/acorn-nut] An **acorn nut**, also referred to as **crown hex nut**, **blind nut**, **cap nut**, **domed cap nut,** or **dome nut** (UK), is a nut that has a domed end on one side.
[src:t-slot-nut/acorn-nut] When used together with a threaded fastener with an external male thread, the domed end encloses the external thread, either to protect the thread or to protect nearby objects from contact with the thread.
[src:t-slot-nut/acorn-nut] In addition, the dome gives a more finished appearance.
[src:t-slot-nut/acorn-nut] Acorn nuts are usually made of brass, steel, stainless steel (low carbon content) or nylon.
[src:t-slot-nut/acorn-nut] They can also be chrome plated and given a mirror finish.
[src:t-slot-nut/acorn-nut] The high acorn nut is wider and higher and will protect extra long studs.
[src:t-slot-nut/acorn-nut] There are also self-locking acorn nuts that have distorted threads in the hex area to create a tight friction fit to prevent the nut from vibrating loose.
[src:t-slot-nut/acorn-nut] There are standards governing the manufacture of acorn nuts.
[src:t-slot-nut/acorn-nut] One is Society of Automotive Engineers (SAE) Standard J483, High and Low Crown (Blind, Acorn) Hex Nuts.
[src:t-slot-nut/acorn-nut] Another is Deutsches Institut für Normung (DIN) 1587, Hexagon Domed Cap Nuts.
[src:t-slot-nut/ansi] The **American National Standards Institute** (**ANSI**) is a private nonprofit organization that oversees the development of voluntary consensus standards for products, services, processes, systems, and personnel in the United States.
[src:t-slot-nut/ansi] The organization also coordinates U.S. standards with international standards so that American products can be used worldwide.
[src:t-slot-nut/ansi] ANSI accredits standards that are developed by representatives of other standards organizations, government agencies, consumer groups, companies, and others.
[src:t-slot-nut/ansi] These standards ensure that the characteristics and performance of products are consistent, that people use the same definitions and terms, and that products are tested the same way.
[src:t-slot-nut/ansi] ANSI also accredits standards developing organizations (SDOs) and provides a searchable directory of accredited standards developers (ASDs).
[src:t-slot-nut/ansi] ANSI similarly accredits organizations that carry out product or personnel certification in accordance with requirements defined in international standards.
[src:t-slot-nut/ansi] The organization's headquarters are in Washington, D.C.
[src:t-slot-nut/ansi] ANSI's operations office is located in New York City.
[src:t-slot-nut/ansi] The ANSI annual operating budget is funded by the sale of publications, membership dues and fees, accreditation services, fee-based programs, and international standards programs.
[src:t-slot-nut/ansi] Many ANSI regulations are incorporated by reference into United States federal statutes (i.e. by OSHA regulations referring to individual ANSI specifications).
[src:t-slot-nut/ansi] ANSI does not make these standards publicly available, and charges money for access to these documents; it further claims that it is copyright infringement for them to be provided to the public by others free of charge.
[src:t-slot-nut/ansi] These assertions have been the subject of criticism and litigation.
[src:t-slot-nut/ansi] ANSI was most likely formed in 1918, when five engineering societies and three government agencies founded the **American Engineering Standards Committee** (**AESC**).
[src:t-slot-nut/ansi] In 1928, the AESC became the **American Standards Association** (**ASA**).
[src:t-slot-nut/ansi] In 1966, the ASA was reorganized and became the **United States of America Standards Institute** (**USASI**).
[src:t-slot-nut/ansi] In February 1969, Ralph Nader harshly criticized the USASI in public remarks as "manifestly deceptive" in several different ways.
[src:t-slot-nut/ansi] He specifically attacked the name USASI as improperly implying some kind of official connection with the federal government of the United States.
[src:t-slot-nut/ansi] had been members of the United Engineering Society (UES).
[src:t-slot-nut/ansi] At the behest of the AIEE, they invited the U.S. government Departments of War, Navy (combined in 1947 to become the Department of Defense or DOD) and Commerce to join in founding a national standards organization.
[src:t-slot-nut/ansi] According to Adam Stanton, the first permanent secretary and head of staff in 1919, AESC started as an ambitious program and little else.
[src:t-slot-nut/ansi] Staff for the first year consisted of one executive, Clifford B.
[src:t-slot-nut/ansi] LePage, who was on loan from a founding member, ASME.
[src:t-slot-nut/ansi] An annual budget of $7,500 was provided by the founding bodies.
[src:t-slot-nut/ansi] In 1931, the organization (renamed ASA in 1928) became affiliated with the U.S.
[src:t-slot-nut/ansi] National Committee of the International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC), which had been formed in 1904 to develop electrical and electronics standards.
[src:t-slot-nut/ansi] ANSI's members are government agencies, organizations, academic and international bodies, and individuals.
[src:t-slot-nut/ansi] In total, the Institute represents the interests of more than 270,000 companies and organizations and 30 million professionals worldwide.
[src:t-slot-nut/ansi] ANSI's market-driven, decentralized approach has been criticized in comparison with more planned and organized international approaches to standardization.
[src:t-slot-nut/ansi] Although ANSI itself does not develop standards, the Institute oversees the development and use of standards by accrediting the procedures of standards developing organizations.
[src:t-slot-nut/ansi] ANSI accreditation signifies that the procedures used by standards developing organizations meet the institute's requirements for openness, balance, consensus, and due process.
[src:t-slot-nut/ansi] ANSI also designates specific standards as American National Standards, or ANS, when the Institute determines that the standards were developed in an environment that is equitable, accessible and responsive to the requirements of various stakeholders.
[src:t-slot-nut/ansi] Voluntary consensus standards quicken the market acceptance of products while making clear how to improve the safety of those products for the protection of consumers.
[src:t-slot-nut/ansi] There are approximately 9,500 American National Standards that carry the ANSI designation.
[src:t-slot-nut/ansi] The institute is the official U.S. representative to the two major international standards organizations, the International Organization for Standardization (ISO), as a founding member, and the International Electrotechnical Commission (IEC), via the U.S.
[src:t-slot-nut/ansi] ANSI participates in almost the entire technical program of both the ISO and the IEC, and administers many key committees and subgroups.
[src:t-slot-nut/ansi] In many instances, U.S. standards are taken forward to ISO and IEC, through ANSI or the USNC, where they are adopted in whole or in part as international standards.
[src:t-slot-nut/ansi] Adoption of ISO and IEC standards as American standards increased from 0.2% in 1986 to 15.5% in May 2012.
[src:t-slot-nut/ansi] Each of the panels works to identify, coordinate, and harmonize voluntary standards relevant to these areas.
[src:t-slot-nut/ansi] In 2009, ANSI and the National Institute of Standards and Technology (NIST) formed the Nuclear Energy Standards Coordination Collaborative (NESCC).
[src:t-slot-nut/ansi] NESCC is a joint initiative to identify and respond to the current need for standards in the nuclear industry.
[src:t-slot-nut/asme-b5] As a Standards Development Organization, ASME continues to develop and maintains nearly 600 codes and standards in a wide range of disciplines including pressure technology, nuclear plants, elevators / escalators, construction, engineering design, and performance testing.
[src:t-slot-nut/asme-b5] Machine Tool standards are developed and maintained by ASME B5 Committee, which operates under ASME's Board on Standardization and Testing.
[src:t-slot-nut/asme-b5] The B5 Standards Committee currently meets once a year in various locations throughout the United States.
[src:t-slot-nut/asme-b5] The meeting is generally held in November and is open to the public.
[src:t-slot-nut/asme-b5] The B5 Technical Committees usually meet in conjunction with the B5 Standards Committee.
[src:t-slot-nut/asme-b5] Some B5 Technical Committees also meet separately in different locations throughout the year.
[src:t-slot-nut/asme-b5] The B5 Standards Committee and its Technical Committees are composed of experts in the field of machine tools.
[src:t-slot-nut/asme-b5] Members of the B5 Standards Committee are classified in the following interest classes: Producer/Manufacturer, Regulatory, Services, General Interest, and User.
[src:t-slot-nut/asme-b5] The B5 Committee works on writing new ASME American National Standards, and revising current ASME B5 and B94 standards.
[src:t-slot-nut/asme-b5] The B5 Standards Committee operates under procedures of the American National Standards Institute (ANSI).
[src:t-slot-nut/asme-b5] The celebration of the 100th meeting in 2022 will mark the 100th consecutive year the ASME B5 committee has met.
[src:t-slot-nut/asme-b5] The following historical information marks only the beginning stages of copious collaborative work and continuous publication, review, and revision of ASME B5 Standards.
[src:t-slot-nut/asme-b5] On May 13, 1914, the ASME Committee on Meetings, Subcommittee on Machine Shop Practice began discussion on standardization of machine shop practices.
[src:t-slot-nut/asme-b5] It wasn't until September 1922 under the procedure of American Standards Association, the B5 committee was organized as a committee dedicated to machine tools.
[src:t-slot-nut/asme-b5] B5 was sponsored by the National Machine Tool Builders’ Association, the Society of Automotive Engineers, Metal Cutting Tool Institute, and The American Society of Mechanical Engineers.
[src:t-slot-nut/asme-b5] On December 2, 1937, the standard for Adjustable Adapters for Multiple Spindle Drilling Heads this standard was approved by the American Standards Association and designated as American Standard (ASA B5.11-1937).
[src:t-slot-nut/asme-b5] Work on the standardization of T-slots started in 1924 and a tentative standard was published in 1927.
[src:t-slot-nut/asme-b5] The first official American Standard for T-slots came in 1941.
[src:t-slot-nut/asme-b5] 11 was organized in New York on December 4, 1928, and B5 Technical Committee No.
[src:t-slot-nut/asme-b5] 4 on Spindle Noses was organized on December 5, 1928.
[src:t-slot-nut/asme-b5] These two committees worked in close cooperation with each other and with manufacturers and users of engine lathes, turret lathes and automatic lathes in developing standards for spindle noses and chucks.
[src:t-slot-nut/asme-b5] 3 on the Standardization of Machine Tapers was appointed in August, 1926, and held its organization meeting in September, 1926, in New Haven, Conn.
[src:t-slot-nut/asme-b5] Three American tapers then in use, the Brown & Sharpe (1860), Morse (1862), and Jarno (1889), and the taper series adopted by William Sellers & Co.(1862) were combined into a compromise standard series which contained twenty-two (22) self-holding taper sizes.
[src:t-slot-nut/asme-b5] The first edition of the Spindle Noses and Tool Shanks for Milling Machines standard, known as B5.18-1943, resulted from intensive effort dating back to 1926 by a special group of milling machine manufacturers.
[src:t-slot-nut/asme-b5] The effort to establish an American standard for Ball Screws began in July 1971 out of a need to obtain a consensus opinion relative to proposals for standardization of ball screw assemblies within the ISO/TC39 sub-committee Working Group 7.
[src:t-slot-nut/asme-b5] Out of this, the subcommittee TC43 was organized with members representing manufacturers, users of ball screws, and others of general interest.
[src:t-slot-nut/asme-b5] TC43 produced ANSI B5.48, which was approved as an American National Standard and published in 1977.
[src:t-slot-nut/asme-b5] Technical subcommittees under ASME B5 address the formulation and maintenance of standards in particular disciplines within the scope of the B5 charter.
[src:t-slot-nut/asme-b5] Membership includes a carefully balanced representation in various interest classifications so that no one group dominates.
[src:t-slot-nut/asme-b5] Some examples of the various interest classifications are: users, manufacturers, consultants, insurance interests, universities, testing laboratories, and government regulatory agencies.
[src:t-slot-nut/asme-b5] There are over 40 Standards that are periodically reviewed to ensure they reflect new developments and technical advances (e.g., new materials, new designs and new applications).
[src:t-slot-nut/asme-b5] Several new standards are under development or being considered in the areas of Tool Holder Interfaces, Machine Performance Evaluation, Micromachining, Energy Assessment, and Robotics.
[src:t-slot-nut/bandsaw] A **bandsaw** (also written **band saw**) is a power saw with a long, sharp blade with two ends welded together to form an oval band.
[src:t-slot-nut/bandsaw] The banded blade of toothed metal is stretched between two or more wheels to cut material.
[src:t-slot-nut/bandsaw] They are used principally in woodworking, metalworking, and lumber milling, but may cut a variety of materials.
[src:t-slot-nut/bandsaw] Advantages include uniform cutting action as a result of an evenly distributed tooth load, and the ability to cut irregular or curved shapes like a jigsaw.
[src:t-slot-nut/bandsaw] The minimum radius of a curve is determined by the width of the band and its kerf.
[src:t-slot-nut/bandsaw] Most bandsaws have two wheels rotating in the same plane, one of which is powered, although some may have three or four to distribute the load.
[src:t-slot-nut/bandsaw] The blade itself can come in a variety of sizes and tooth pitches (teeth per inch, or TPI), which enables the machine to be highly versatile and able to cut a wide variety of materials including wood, metal and plastic.
[src:t-slot-nut/bandsaw] A band saw is recommended for use in cutting metal as it produces much less toxic fumes and particulates when compared with an angle grinder or reciprocating saw.
[src:t-slot-nut/bandsaw] Almost all bandsaws today are powered by an electric motor.
[src:t-slot-nut/bandsaw] The idea of the bandsaw dates back to at least 1809, when William Newberry received a British patent for the idea, but bandsaws remained impractical largely because of the inability to produce accurate and durable blades using the technology of the day.
[src:t-slot-nut/bandsaw] Constant flexing of the blade over the wheels caused either the material or the joint welding it into a loop to fail.
[src:t-slot-nut/bandsaw] Nearly 40 years passed before Frenchwoman Anne Paulin Crepin devised a welding technique overcoming this hurdle.
[src:t-slot-nut/bandsaw] She applied for a patent in 1846, and soon afterward sold the right to employ it to manufacturer A.
[src:t-slot-nut/bandsaw] Combining this method with new steel alloys and advanced tempering techniques allowed Perin to create the first modern bandsaw blade.
[src:t-slot-nut/bandsaw] The first American bandsaw patent was granted to Benjamin Barker of Ellsworth, Maine, in January 1836.
[src:t-slot-nut/bandsaw] The first factory produced and commercially available bandsaw in the U.S. was by a design of Paul Prybil.
[src:t-slot-nut/bandsaw] Power hacksaws (with reciprocating blades) were once common in the metalworking industries, but bandsaws and cold saws have mostly displaced them.
[src:t-slot-nut/bandsaw] Many workshops in residential garages or basements and in light industry contain small or medium-sized bandsaws that can cut wood, metal, or plastic.
[src:t-slot-nut/bandsaw] Often a general-purpose blade is left in place, although blades optimized for wood or metal can be switched out when volume of use warrants.
[src:t-slot-nut/bandsaw] Most residential and commercial bandsaws are of the vertical type mounted on a bench or a cabinet stand.
[src:t-slot-nut/bandsaw] Portable power tool versions, including cordless models, are also common in recent decades, allowing building contractors to bring them along on the truck to the jobsite.
[src:t-slot-nut/bandsaw] Saws for cutting meat are typically of all stainless steel construction with easy to clean features.
[src:t-slot-nut/bandsaw] The blades either have fine teeth with heat treated tips, or have plain or scalloped knife edges.
[src:t-slot-nut/bandsaw] Bandsaws dedicated to industrial metal-cutting use, such as for structural steel in fabrication shops and for bar stock in machine shops, are available in vertical and horizontal designs.
[src:t-slot-nut/bandsaw] Typical band speeds range from 40 ft/min (0.20 m/s) to 5,000 ft/min (25 m/s), although specialized bandsaws are built for friction cutting of hard metals and run band speeds of 15,000 ft/min (76 m/s).
[src:t-slot-nut/bandsaw] Metal-cutting bandsaws are usually equipped with brushes or brushwheels to prevent chips from becoming stuck in between the blade's teeth.
[src:t-slot-nut/bandsaw] Systems which cool the blade with cutting fluid are also common equipment on metal-cutting bandsaws.
[src:t-slot-nut/bandsaw] The coolant washes away swarf and keeps the blade cool and lubricated.
[src:t-slot-nut/bandsaw] Horizontal bandsaws hold the workpiece stationary while the blade swings down through the cut.
[src:t-slot-nut/bandsaw] This configuration is used to cut long materials such as pipe or bar stock to length.
[src:t-slot-nut/bandsaw] Thus it is an important part of the facilities in most machine shops.
[src:t-slot-nut/bandsaw] The horizontal design is not useful for cutting curves or complicated shapes.
[src:t-slot-nut/bandsaw] Small horizontal bandsaws typically employ a gravity feed alone, retarded to an adjustable degree by a coil spring; on industrial models, the rate of descent is usually controlled by a hydraulic cylinder that bleeds through an adjustable valve.
[src:t-slot-nut/bandsaw] When the saw is set up for a cut, the operator raises the saw, positions the material to be cut underneath the blade, and then turns on the saw.
[src:t-slot-nut/bandsaw] The blade slowly descends into the material, cutting it as the band blade moves.
[src:t-slot-nut/bandsaw] When the cut is complete, a switch is tripped and the saw automatically turns off.
[src:t-slot-nut/bandsaw] More sophisticated versions of this type of saw are partially or entirely automated (via PLC or CNC) for high-volume cutting of machining blanks.
[src:t-slot-nut/bandsaw] Such machines provide a stream of cutting fluid recirculated from a sump, in the same manner that a CNC machining center does.
[src:t-slot-nut/bandsaw] A vertical bandsaw, also called a contour saw, keeps the blade's path stationary while the workpiece is moved across it.
[src:t-slot-nut/bandsaw] This type of saw can be used to cut out complex shapes and angles.
[src:t-slot-nut/bandsaw] The part may be fed into the blade manually or with a power assist mechanism.
[src:t-slot-nut/bandsaw] This type of metal-cutting bandsaw is often equipped with a built-in blade welder.
[src:t-slot-nut/bandsaw] This not only allows the operator to repair broken blades or fabricate new blades quickly, but also allows for the blade to be purposely cut, routed through the center of a part, and re-welded in order to make interior cuts.
[src:t-slot-nut/bandsaw] These saws are often fitted with a built-in air blower to cool the blade and to blow chips away from the cut area giving the operator a clear view of the work.
[src:t-slot-nut/bandsaw] This type of saw is also built in a woodworking version.
[src:t-slot-nut/bandsaw] The woodworking type is generally of much lighter construction and does not incorporate a power feed mechanism, coolant, or welder.
[src:t-slot-nut/bandsaw] Advancements have also been made in the bandsaw blades used to cut metals.
[src:t-slot-nut/bandsaw] Bimetal blades with high speed steel teeth, including cobalt grades, are now the norm.
[src:t-slot-nut/bandsaw] The development of new tooth geometries and tooth pitches has produced increased production rates and greater blade life.
[src:t-slot-nut/bandsaw] New materials and processes such as M51 steel and the cryogenic treatment of blades have produced results that were thought impossible just a few years ago.
[src:t-slot-nut/bandsaw] New machines have been developed to automate the welding process of bandsaw blades as well.
[src:t-slot-nut/bandsaw] Timber mills use very large bandsaws for ripping lumber; they are preferred over circular saws for ripping because they can accommodate large-diameter timber and because of their smaller kerf (cut size), resulting in less waste.
[src:t-slot-nut/bandsaw] There are also small portable sawmills consisting of a somewhat smaller bandsaw mounted on a guiding table, which are called bandsaw mills (band saw mills, band sawmills).
[src:t-slot-nut/bandsaw] Like chain saw mills (a chainsaw on a guiding table), they can be used inexpensively by one or two people out in the field.
[src:t-slot-nut/bandsaw] These tools may be used by off-gridders and those doing small scale lumber processing in remote areas.
[src:t-slot-nut/bandsaw] Today, even these mills may be powered by electricity.
[src:t-slot-nut/bandsaw] In a full-size sawmill, the blades are mounted on wheels with a diameter large enough not to cause metal fatigue due to flexing when the blade repeatedly changes from a circular to a straight profile.
[src:t-slot-nut/bandsaw] It is stretched very tight (with fatigue strength of the saw metal being the limiting factor).
[src:t-slot-nut/bandsaw] Bandsaws of this size need to have a deformation worked into them that counteracts the forces and heating of operation.
[src:t-slot-nut/bandsaw] They also need to be removed and serviced at regular intervals.
[src:t-slot-nut/bandsaw] Sawfilers or sawdoctors are the craftsmen responsible for this work.
[src:t-slot-nut/bandsaw] The shape of the tooth gullet is highly optimized and designed by the sawyer and sawfiler.
[src:t-slot-nut/bandsaw] It varies according to the mill, as well as the type and condition of the wood.
[src:t-slot-nut/bandsaw] Frozen logs often require a "frost notch" ground into the gullet to break the chips.
[src:t-slot-nut/bandsaw] The shape of the tooth gullet is created when the blade is manufactured and its shape is automatically maintained with each sharpening.
[src:t-slot-nut/bandsaw] The sawfiler will need to maintain the grinding wheel's profile with periodic dressing of the wheel.
[src:t-slot-nut/bandsaw] Proper tracking of the blade is crucial to accurate cutting and considerably reduces blade breakage.
[src:t-slot-nut/bandsaw] The first step to ensuring good tracking is to check that the two bandwheels or flywheels are co-planar.
[src:t-slot-nut/bandsaw] This can be done by placing a straightedge across the front of the wheels and adjusting until each wheel touches on both its top and bottom.
[src:t-slot-nut/bandsaw] Rotate the wheels with the blade in position and properly tensioned and check that the tracking is correct.
[src:t-slot-nut/bandsaw] Now install the blade guide rollers and leave a gap of about 1mm between the back of the blade and the guide flange.
[src:t-slot-nut/bandsaw] The teeth of blades that have become narrow through repeated sharpening will foul the front edge of the guide rollers due to their kerf set and force the blade out of alignment.
[src:t-slot-nut/bandsaw] This can be remedied by cutting of a small step on the rollers' front edges to accommodate the protruding teeth.
[src:t-slot-nut/bandsaw] Ideally the rollers should be crowned, (see belt and pulley systems) a configuration that assists in the proper tracking of bands and belts, at the same time allowing clearance for the set of the teeth.
[src:t-slot-nut/bandsaw] Head saws are large bandsaws that make the initial cuts in a log.
[src:t-slot-nut/bandsaw] They generally have a 2 to 3 in (51 to 76 mm) tooth space on the cutting edge and *sliver teeth* on the back.
[src:t-slot-nut/bandsaw] Sliver teeth are non-cutting teeth designed to wipe slivers out of the way when the blade needs to back out of a cut.
[src:t-slot-nut/bandsaw] A resaw is a large bandsaw optimized for cutting timber along the grain to reduce larger sections into smaller sections or veneers.
[src:t-slot-nut/bandsaw] Resawing veneers requires a wide blade—commonly 2 to 3 in (51 to 76 mm)—with a small kerf to minimize waste.
[src:t-slot-nut/bandsaw] Resaw blades of up to 1 in (25 mm) may be fitted to a standard bandsaw.
[src:t-slot-nut/bandsaw] Double cut saws have cutting teeth on both sides.
[src:t-slot-nut/bandsaw] They are generally very large, similar in size to a head saw.
[src:t-slot-nut/bandsaw] Automatic bandsaws feature preset feed rate, return, fall, part feeding, and part clamping.
[src:t-slot-nut/bandsaw] These are used in production environments where having a machine operator per saw is not practical.
[src:t-slot-nut/bandsaw] One operator can feed and unload many automatic saws.
[src:t-slot-nut/bandsaw] Some automatic saws rely on numerical control to not only cut faster, but to be more precise and perform more complex miter cuts.
[src:t-slot-nut/bandsaw] At least two teeth must be in contact with the workpiece at all times to avoid stripping off the teeth.
[src:t-slot-nut/barrel-nut] is fastened to the receiver with a nut, referred to as a barrel nut.
[src:t-slot-nut/barrel-nut] A **barrel nut** (also known as **steel cross dowel** or **dowel nut**) is a specialized forged nut, and is commonly used in aerospace and ready-to-assemble furniture applications.
[src:t-slot-nut/barrel-nut] It is used to bolt thin sheet metal parts to larger, often billet or forged, parts.
[src:t-slot-nut/barrel-nut] The barrel nut is a round slug, or formed sheet metal part with threads perpendicular to the length of the nut.
[src:t-slot-nut/barrel-nut] The nut sits in a hole inside the forging and a standard bolt is threaded into the barrel nut from outside the sheet metal.
[src:t-slot-nut/barrel-nut] They are preferred over a standard nut and bolt, because they do not require a flange to be machined or forged onto the receiving part, thus reducing weight.
[src:t-slot-nut/barrel-nut] Furniture cross dowel barrel nuts are cylindrical shaped metal nuts (metal dowels) used with furniture connector bolts to join two pieces of wood.
[src:t-slot-nut/barrel-nut] The inside threaded hole is unusual in that it passes through the sides of the dowel.
[src:t-slot-nut/barrel-nut] To install, the pieces of wood to be joined are aligned, then a bolt hole is drilled through one piece of wood and into the other.
[src:t-slot-nut/barrel-nut] A dowel hole is drilled laterally across the bolt hole and the cross dowel is inserted into it.
[src:t-slot-nut/barrel-nut] The end of the cross dowel is slotted so that a screwdriver can be inserted to rotate the dowel so that its threaded shaft aligns with the bolt hole.
[src:t-slot-nut/barrel-nut] The furniture connector bolt is then inserted into the bolt hole and screwed into the cross dowel until the wood pieces are held tightly together.
[src:t-slot-nut/barrel-nut] Barrel nuts are also common in flat-pack furniture, where long bolts and barrel nuts are used to hold together T joints in chipboard sheets.
[src:t-slot-nut/cage-nut] A **cage nut** or **caged nut** (also called a captive or clip nut) consists of a (usually square) nut in a spring steel cage which wraps around the nut.
[src:t-slot-nut/cage-nut] The cage has two wings that when compressed allow the cage to be inserted into the square holes, for example, in the mounting rails of equipment racks.
[src:t-slot-nut/cage-nut] When the wings are released, they hold the nut in position behind the hole.
[src:t-slot-nut/cage-nut] Cage nuts conforming to this description were patented in 1952 and 1953.
[src:t-slot-nut/cage-nut] The original design requires an insertion tool to install a cage nut into a hole.
[src:t-slot-nut/cage-nut] Newer designs featuring squeeze-and-release tabs allow for tool-less installation.
[src:t-slot-nut/cage-nut] Other newer designs even swap the nut for one or two threaded studs, which allow installers to let the equipment rest on the mounting studs as they fasten the nuts to secure the equipment.
[src:t-slot-nut/cage-nut] The square-hole cage nut can be used wherever a square hole can be punched.
[src:t-slot-nut/cage-nut] An older type of captive nut uses a spring clip that holds the nut and slides on the edge of a thin sheet.
[src:t-slot-nut/cage-nut] While this type of cage nut can only position the nut a fixed distance from the edge of a thin plate, it works equally well with square and round holes.
[src:t-slot-nut/cage-nut] A patent for such a nut was granted in 1946.
[src:t-slot-nut/cage-nut] Using cage nuts provides several benefits over threaded holes.
[src:t-slot-nut/cage-nut] It permits a range of choice of nut and bolt size (e.g. metric vs English) in the field, long after the equipment has been manufactured.
[src:t-slot-nut/cage-nut] Second, if a screw is over-tightened, the nut can be replaced, unlike a pre-threaded hole, where a hole with stripped threads becomes unusable.
[src:t-slot-nut/cage-nut] Third, cage nuts are easy to use on materials too thin or soft to be threaded.
[src:t-slot-nut/cage-nut] The nut is usually slightly loose in the cage to allow for minor adjustments in alignment.
[src:t-slot-nut/cage-nut] This reduces the likelihood that the threads will be stripped during equipment installation and removal.
[src:t-slot-nut/cage-nut] The dimensions of the spring steel clip determine thickness of the panel to which the nut may be clipped.
[src:t-slot-nut/cage-nut] In the case of square-hole cage nuts, the clip dimensions determine the range of hole sizes to which the clip will securely hold the nut.
[src:t-slot-nut/cage-nut] In the case of slide-on cage nuts, the clip dimensions determine the distance from the panel edge to the hole.
[src:t-slot-nut/cage-nut] A common use for cage nuts is to mount equipment in square-holed 19-inch racks (the most common type), with 0.375 inches (9.5 mm) square-hole size.
[src:t-slot-nut/cage-nut] There are four common sizes: UNF 10–32 and, to a lesser extent, UNC 12–24 are generally used in the United States; elsewhere, M5 (5 mm outside diameter and 0.8 mm pitch) for light and medium equipment and M6 for heavier equipment, such as servers.
[src:t-slot-nut/cage-nut] Although some modern rack-mount equipment has bolt-free mounting compatible with square-hole racks, many rack-mount components are generally mounted with cage nuts.
[src:t-slot-nut/castellated-nut] A **castellated nut**, sometimes referred to as a **castle nut**, is a nut with slots or notches cut into one end.
[src:t-slot-nut/castellated-nut] The name comes from the nut's resemblance to the crenellated parapet of a medieval castle.
[src:t-slot-nut/castellated-nut] Castellated nuts are sometimes incorrectly referred to as **castigated nuts**.
[src:t-slot-nut/castellated-nut] While castellated nuts are often referred to as **slotted nuts**, from a technical perspective, slotted nuts differ slightly from castellated nuts.
[src:t-slot-nut/castellated-nut] Castellated nuts are formed with a round section at the top where the slots are located.
[src:t-slot-nut/castellated-nut] Slotted nuts do not have this rounded modification.
[src:t-slot-nut/castellated-nut] The flat sides of slotted nuts extend fully from the top to the bottom of the nut.
[src:t-slot-nut/castellated-nut] Both castellated and slotted nuts are designed to use a pin (usually a split pin) that fits through the slots and through a hole in the screw to which the nut is attached.
[src:t-slot-nut/castellated-nut] This pin prevents the nut from turning and loosening.
[src:t-slot-nut/castellated-nut] Compared with slotted nuts, castellated nuts allow the cotter pin to be confined closer to the margins of the nut itself, providing added security.
[src:t-slot-nut/castellated-nut] The bolt has one or two holes drilled through its threaded end.
[src:t-slot-nut/castellated-nut] The nut is torqued properly and then, if the slot is not aligned with the hole in the fastener, the nut is rotated forward to the nearest slot.
[src:t-slot-nut/castellated-nut] The nut is then secured with a split pin/cotter pin, R-clip or safety wire.
[src:t-slot-nut/castellated-nut] Castellated nuts are used in low-torque applications, such as holding a wheel bearing in place.
[src:t-slot-nut/t-slot-nut] A **T-slot nut** is used with a threaded clamp to position and secure pieces being worked on in a workshop.
[src:t-slot-nut/t-slot-nut] The T-slot nut slides along a T-slot track, which is set in workbench or table for a router, drill press, or bandsaw.
[src:t-slot-nut/t-slot-nut] T-slot nuts are also used with T-slot structural framing to build a variety of industrial structures and machines.
[src:t-slot-nut/t-slot-nut] A **T-slot bolt** is generally stronger than a T-slot nut and hex-head cap screw.
[src:t-slot-nut/t-slot-nut] A heavy-duty T-slot nut with a M12 bolt is rated to support 10000 N (about 1 imperial ton at rest).
[src:t-slot-nut/t-slot-nut] Profile 40×40 (40 mm by 40 mm, with 8 mm grooves) extruded aluminum profile and the T-slot nuts to fit into them comprised the first modular system developed for use in mechanical engineering in 1980 by item Industrietechnik.
[src:t-slot-nut/t-slot-nut] The item aluminum framing system has since been expanded to include a variety of t-slot nuts that have been designed for specific applications.
[src:t-slot-nut/t-slot-nut] The item system is very similar to the "channel-and-groove design" used in some toys.
